<p><br />
The following is a list of <a href="/wiki/Gods" class="mw-redirect" title="Gods">gods</a>, <a href="/wiki/Goddesses" class="mw-redirect" title="Goddesses">goddesses</a> and many other divine and semi-divine figures from ancient <a href="/wiki/Greek_mythology" title="Greek mythology">Greek mythology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_religion" title="Ancient Greek religion">ancient Greek religion</a>. The list does not include creatures; for these, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Greek_mythological_creatures" title="List of Greek mythological creatures">List of Greek mythological creatures</a>.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Immortals">Immortals</span></h2>
<p>The Greeks created images of their deities for many purposes. A temple would house the statue of a god or goddess, or multiple deities, and might be decorated with <a href="/wiki/Relief" title="Relief">relief</a> scenes depicting myths. Divine images were common on coins. Drinking cups and other <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_pottery" class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient Greek pottery">vessels</a> were painted with scenes from Greek myths.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Major_gods_and_goddesses">Major gods and goddesses</span></h3>
<table class="wikitable" width="100%">

<tbody><tr>
<th>Deity
</th>
<th>Description
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg" class="image"><img alt="NAMA Aphrodite Syracuse.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/160px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="409" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/240px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg/320px-NAMA_Aphrodite_Syracuse.jpg 2x" data-file-width="674" data-file-height="1721" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀφροδίτη</span>, <i>Aphroditē</i>)
<p>Goddess of beauty, love, desire, and pleasure. In <a href="/wiki/Hesiod" title="Hesiod">Hesiod</a>'s <i>Theogony</i> (188–206), she was born from sea-foam and the severed genitals of <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a>; in <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a>'s <i>Iliad</i> (5.370–417), she is daughter of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dione_(Titaness)" title="Dione (Titaness)">Dione</a>. She was married to <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, but bore him no children. She had many lovers, most notably <a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a>, to whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Harmonia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Harmonia (mythology)">Harmonia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(mythology)" title="Phobos (mythology)">Phobos</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deimos (mythology)">Deimos</a>. She was also a lover to <a href="/wiki/Adonis" title="Adonis">Adonis</a> and <a href="/wiki/Anchises" title="Anchises">Anchises</a>, to whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Aeneas" title="Aeneas">Aeneas</a>. She is usually depicted as a naked or semi-nude beautiful woman. Her symbols include <a href="/wiki/Myrtus_communis" title="Myrtus communis">myrtle</a>, roses, and the <a href="/wiki/Scallop" title="Scallop">scallop</a> shell. Her sacred animals include doves and sparrows. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Venus_(mythology)" title="Venus (mythology)">Venus</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Pothos,_lira,_dan_angsa_(inv_6253_MANN).jpg" class="image"><img alt="Pothos, lira, dan angsa (inv 6253 MANN).jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/160px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="257" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/240px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg/320px-Pothos%2C_lira%2C_dan_angsa_%28inv_6253_MANN%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="374" data-file-height="600" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀπόλλων</span>, <i>Apóllōn</i>)
<p>God of music, arts, knowledge, healing, plague, prophecy, poetry, manly beauty, and archery. He is the son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leto" title="Leto">Leto</a>, and the twin brother of <a href="/wiki/Artemis" title="Artemis">Artemis</a>. Both Apollo and Artemis use a bow and arrow. Apollo is depicted as young, beardless, handsome and athletic. In myth, he can be cruel and destructive, and his love affairs are rarely happy. He is often accompanied by the Muses. His most famous temple is in <a href="/wiki/Delphi" title="Delphi">Delphi</a>, where he established his oracular shrine. His signs and symbols include the <a href="/wiki/Laurel_wreath" title="Laurel wreath">laurel wreath</a>, bow and arrow, and <a href="/wiki/Lyre" title="Lyre">lyre</a>. His sacred animals include <a href="/wiki/Roe_deer" title="Roe deer">roe deer</a>, swans, and pythons. Some late Roman and Greek poetry and mythography identifies him as a sun-god, equivalent to Roman <a href="/wiki/Sol_(Roman_mythology)" title="Sol (Roman mythology)">Sol</a> and Greek <a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Ares Canope Villa Adriana b.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/160px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="320" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/240px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg/320px-Ares_Canope_Villa_Adriana_b.jpg 2x" data-file-width="875" data-file-height="1750" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἄρης</span>, <i>Árēs</i>)
<p>God of courage, war, bloodshed, and violence. The son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a>, he was depicted as a beardless youth, either nude with a helmet and spear or sword, or as an armed warrior. <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a> portrays him as moody and unreliable, and as being the most unpopular god on earth and Olympus (<i>Iliad</i> 5.890–1). He generally represents the chaos of war in contrast to <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a>, a goddess of military strategy and skill. Ares is known for cuckolding his brother <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, conducting an affair with his wife <a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a>. His sacred animals include vultures, venomous snakes, dogs, and boars. His Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Mars_(mythology)" title="Mars (mythology)">Mars</a> by contrast was regarded as the dignified ancestor of the Roman people.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Diane de Versailles Leochares.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/160px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="246" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/240px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg/320px-Diane_de_Versailles_Leochares.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="1230" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Artemis" title="Artemis">Artemis</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἄρτεμις</span>, <i>Ártemis</i>)
<p>Virgin goddess of the hunt, wilderness, animals, the Moon and young girls. In later times, Artemis became associated with bows and arrows. She is the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leto" title="Leto">Leto</a>, and twin sister of <a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a>. In art she is often depicted as a young woman dressed in a short knee-length <a href="/wiki/Chiton_(costume)" title="Chiton (costume)">chiton</a> and equipped with a hunting bow and a quiver of arrows. Her attributes include hunting spears, animal pelts, <a href="/wiki/Deer" title="Deer">deer</a> and other wild animals. Her sacred animal is a deer. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Diana_(mythology)" title="Diana (mythology)">Diana</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Mattei Athena Louvre Ma530 n2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/160px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="320" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/240px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg/320px-Mattei_Athena_Louvre_Ma530_n2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="3600" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀθηνᾶ</span>, <i>Athēnâ</i>)
<p>Goddess of reason, wisdom, intelligence, skill, peace, warfare, battle strategy, and handicrafts. According to most traditions, she was born from Zeus's forehead, fully formed and armored. She is depicted as being crowned with a crested helm, armed with shield and spear, and wearing the <a href="/wiki/Aegis" title="Aegis">aegis</a> over a long dress. Poets describe her as "grey-eyed" or having especially bright, keen eyes. She is a special patron of <a href="/wiki/Greek_hero" class="mw-redirect" title="Greek hero">heroes</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a>. She is the patron of the city Athens (from which she takes her name) and is attributed to various inventions in arts and literature. Her symbol is the <a href="/wiki/Olive" title="Olive">olive</a> tree. She is commonly shown as being accompanied by her sacred animal, the owl. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Minerva" title="Minerva">Minerva</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Demeter Altemps Inv8546.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/160px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="366" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/240px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg/320px-Demeter_Altemps_Inv8546.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1550" data-file-height="3550" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Demeter" title="Demeter">Demeter</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Δημήτηρ</span>, <i>Dēmḗtēr</i>)
<p>Goddess of grain, agriculture, harvest, growth, and nourishment. Demeter, whose Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Ceres_(mythology)" title="Ceres (mythology)">Ceres</a>, is a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and was swallowed and then regurgitated by her father. She is a sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>, by whom she bore <a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a>, who is also known as Kore, i.e. "the girl." One of the central myths associated with Demeter involves <a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a>' abduction of Persephone and Demeter's lengthy search for her. Demeter is one of the main deities of the <a href="/wiki/Eleusinian_Mysteries" title="Eleusinian Mysteries">Eleusinian Mysteries</a>, in which the rites seemed to center around Demeter's search for and reunion with her daughter, which symbolized both the rebirth of crops in spring and the rebirth of the initiates after death. She is depicted as a mature woman, often crowned and holding sheafs of <a href="/wiki/Wheat" title="Wheat">wheat</a> and a torch.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Her symbols are the <a href="/wiki/Cornucopia" title="Cornucopia">cornucopia</a>, wheat-ears, the winged serpent, and the lotus staff. Her sacred animals include pigs and snakes.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Dionysos Louvre Ma87 n2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/160px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="315" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/240px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg/320px-Dionysos_Louvre_Ma87_n2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1700" data-file-height="3350" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Διόνυσος</span>, <i>Diónusos</i>)/<b>Bacchus</b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Βάκχος</span>, <i>Bákkhos</i>)
<p>God of wine, fruitfulness, parties, festivals, madness, chaos, drunkenness, vegetation, ecstasy, and the theater. He is the twice-born son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a>, in that Zeus snatched him from his mother's womb and stitched Dionysus into his own thigh and carried him until he was ready to be born. In art he is depicted as either an older bearded god (particularly before 430 BC) or an <a href="/wiki/Effeminacy" title="Effeminacy">effeminate</a>, long-haired youth (particularly after 430 BC). His attributes include the <a href="/wiki/Thyrsus" title="Thyrsus">thyrsus</a>, a drinking cup, the grape vine, and a crown of <a href="/wiki/Ivy" class="mw-redirect" title="Ivy">ivy</a>. He is often in the company of his <a href="/wiki/Thiasos" class="mw-redirect" title="Thiasos">thiasos</a>, a group of attendants including <a href="/wiki/Satyr" title="Satyr">satyrs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maenad" title="Maenad">maenads</a>, and his old tutor <a href="/wiki/Silenus" title="Silenus">Silenus</a>. The consort of Dionysus was <a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a>. It was once held that Dionysius was a later addition to the Greek pantheon, but the discovery of <a href="/wiki/Linear_B" title="Linear B">Linear B</a> tablets confirm his status as a deity from an early period. Bacchus was another name for him in Greek, and came into common usage among the Romans.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> His sacred animals include dolphins, serpents, tigers, and donkeys.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/160px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="296" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/240px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg/320px-Hades-et-Cerberus-III.jpg 2x" data-file-width="489" data-file-height="904" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">ᾍδης</span>, <i>Háidēs</i>)/<b><a href="/wiki/Pluto_(mythology)" title="Pluto (mythology)">Pluto</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Πλούτων</span>, <i>Ploutōn</i>)
<p>King of the underworld and the dead. God of wealth. His consort is <a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a>. His attributes are the <a href="/wiki/Drinking_horn" title="Drinking horn">drinking horn</a> or <a href="/wiki/Cornucopia" title="Cornucopia">cornucopia</a>, key, sceptre, and the three-headed dog <a href="/wiki/Cerberus" title="Cerberus">Cerberus</a>. His sacred animals include the screech owl. He was one of three sons of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and thus sovereign over one of the three realms of the universe, the underworld. As a <a href="/wiki/Chthonic" title="Chthonic">chthonic</a> god, however, his place among the Olympians is ambiguous. In the <a href="/wiki/Mystery_religions" class="mw-redirect" title="Mystery religions">mystery religions</a> and Athenian literature, Plouton ("the Rich one") was his preferred name, because of the idea that all riches came from the earth. The term <i>Hades</i> was used in this literature to refer to the underworld itself. The Romans translated <i>Plouton</i> as <a href="/wiki/Dis_Pater" class="mw-redirect" title="Dis Pater">Dis Pater</a> ("the Rich Father") or Pluto.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Vulcan Coustou Louvre MR1814.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/160px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="241" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/240px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg/320px-Vulcan_Coustou_Louvre_MR1814.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="3008" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἥφαιστος</span>, <i>Hḗphaistos</i>)
<p>God of fire, metalworking, and crafts. Either the son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a> or Hera alone, he is the smith of the gods and the husband of the adulterous <a href="/wiki/Aphrodite" title="Aphrodite">Aphrodite</a>. He was usually depicted as a bearded, crippled man with hammer, tongs, and anvil, and sometimes riding a donkey. His sacred animals include the donkey, the guard dog, and the crane. Among his creations was the armor of <a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a>. Hephaestus used the fire of the forge as a creative force, but his Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Vulcan_(mythology)" title="Vulcan (mythology)">Vulcan</a> was feared for his destructive potential and associated with the <a href="/wiki/Volcanism" title="Volcanism">volcanic power</a> of the earth.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hera Campana Louvre Ma2283.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/160px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="292" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/240px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg/320px-Hera_Campana_Louvre_Ma2283.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1947" data-file-height="3551" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἥρα</span>, <i>Hḗra</i>)
<p>Queen of the gods, and goddess of marriage, women, childbirth, heirs, kings, and empires. She is the wife and sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>, and the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>. She was usually depicted as a regal woman in the prime of her life, wearing a diadem and veil and holding a lotus-tipped staff. Although she is the goddess of marriage, Zeus's many infidelities drive her to jealousy and vengefulness. Her sacred animals include the heifer, the peacock, and the cuckoo. Her Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Juno_(mythology)" title="Juno (mythology)">Juno</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hermes Ingenui Pio-Clementino Inv544.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/160px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="350" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/240px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg/320px-Hermes_Ingenui_Pio-Clementino_Inv544.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="3500" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hermes" title="Hermes">Hermes</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἑρμῆς</span>, <i>Hērmês</i>)
<p>God of boundaries, travel, communication, trade, language, thieves and writing. Hermes was also responsible for protecting livestock and presided over the spheres associated with fertility, music, luck, and deception.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The son of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Maia (mythology)">Maia</a>, Hermes is the messenger of the gods, and a <a href="/wiki/Psychopomp" title="Psychopomp">psychopomp</a> who leads the souls of the dead into the afterlife. He was depicted either as a handsome and athletic beardless youth, or as an older bearded man. His attributes include the herald's wand or <a href="/wiki/Caduceus" title="Caduceus">caduceus</a>, winged sandals, and a traveler's cap. His sacred animals include the tortoise. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(mythology)" title="Mercury (mythology)">Mercury</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Hestia Giustiniani.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/160px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="300" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/240px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg/320px-Hestia_Giustiniani.jpg 2x" data-file-width="483" data-file-height="907" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Hestia" title="Hestia">Hestia</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἑστία</span>, <i>Hestía</i>)
<p>Virgin goddess of the hearth, home, and chastity. She is a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a>, and a sister of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>. Not often identifiable in Greek art, she appeared as a modestly veiled woman. Her symbols are the hearth and kettle. In some accounts, she gave up her seat as one of the <a href="/wiki/Twelve_Olympians" title="Twelve Olympians">Twelve Olympians</a> in favor of <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a>, and she plays little role in Greek myths. Her Roman counterpart <a href="/wiki/Vesta_(mythology)" title="Vesta (mythology)">Vesta</a>, however, was a major deity of the Roman state.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg" class="image"><img alt="0036MAN Poseidon.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/160px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="213" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/240px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg/320px-0036MAN_Poseidon.jpg 2x" data-file-width="743" data-file-height="990" /></a>
</td>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ποσειδῶν</span>, <i>Poseidôn</i>)
<p>God of the sea, rivers, floods, droughts, and earthquakes. He is a son of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>, and the brother of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a>. He rules one of the three realms of the universe, as king of the sea and the waters. In art he is depicted as a mature man of sturdy build, often with a luxuriant beard, and holding a <a href="/wiki/Trident" title="Trident">trident</a>. His sacred animals include the horse and the dolphin. His wedding with <a href="/wiki/Amphitrite" title="Amphitrite">Amphitrite</a> is often presented as a <a href="/wiki/Thiasos#Other_thiasoi" class="mw-redirect" title="Thiasos">triumphal procession</a>. In some stories he rapes Medusa, leading to her transformation into a hideous Gorgon and also to the birth of their two children, Pegasus and Chrysaor. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)" title="Neptune (mythology)">Neptune</a>.
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="200px" align="center"><a href="/wiki/File:Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Jupiter Smyrna Louvre Ma13.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/160px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg" decoding="async" width="160" height="333" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/240px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg/320px-Jupiter_Smyrna_Louvre_Ma13.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="3750" /></a>
</td>
<td><b> <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a></b> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ζεύς</span>, <i>Zeús</i>)
<p>King of the gods, ruler of Mount Olympus, and god of the sky, weather, thunder, lightning, law, order, and justice. He is the youngest son of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhea_(mythology)" title="Rhea (mythology)">Rhea</a>. He overthrew Cronus and gained the sovereignty of heaven for himself. In art he is depicted as a regal, mature man with a sturdy figure and dark beard. His usual attributes are the royal scepter and the lightning bolt. His sacred animals include the eagle and the bull. His Roman counterpart is <a href="/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)" title="Jupiter (mythology)">Jupiter</a>, also known as Jove.
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Primordial_deities"><a href="/wiki/Greek_primordial_deities" title="Greek primordial deities">Primordial deities</a></span></h3>

<td>The personification of nothingness from which all of existence sprang. Depicted as a void. Initially genderless, later on described as female.

</td></tr>

</td></tr>
<tr>

<td colspan="3" style="text-align:center;"><b>The Twelve Titans</b>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Κοῖος</span> (<i>Koîos</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Coeus" title="Coeus">Coeus</a></td>
<td>Titan of intellect and the axis of heaven around which the constellations revolved.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Κρεῖος</span> (<i>Kreîos</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Crius" title="Crius">Crius</a></td>
<td>The least individualized of the Twelve Titans, he is the father of <a href="/wiki/Astraeus" title="Astraeus">Astraeus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pallas_(Titan)" title="Pallas (Titan)">Pallas</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Perses_(Titan)" title="Perses (Titan)">Perses</a>. Implied to be the Titan of constellations.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Κρόνος</span> (<i>Krónos</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a></td>
<td>Titan of harvests and personification of destructive time. The leader of the Titans, who overthrew his father <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a> only to be overthrown in turn by his son, <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>. Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/Chronos" title="Chronos">Chronos</a>.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ὑπερίων</span> (<i>Hyperíōn</i>)</td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Hyperion_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Hyperion (mythology)">Hyperion</a></td>
<td>Titan of light. With <a href="/wiki/Theia" title="Theia">Theia</a>, he is the father of <a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a> (the sun), <a href="/wiki/Selene" title="Selene">Selene</a> (the moon), and <a href="/wiki/Eos" title="Eos">Eos</a> (the dawn).
</td></tr>
<tr>

She is the sister and consort of <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a>, and mother of <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hades" title="Hades">Hades</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a>, <a href="/wiki/Demeter" title="Demeter">Demeter</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hestia" title="Hestia">Hestia</a>.

<td><a href="/wiki/Tethys_(mythology)" title="Tethys (mythology)">Tethys</a></td>
<td>Titaness of fresh-water, and the mother of the rivers, springs, streams, fountains, and clouds.
</td></tr>

<h3><span id="Gigantes_and_other_.22giants.22"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Gigantes_and_other_&quot;giants&quot;">Gigantes and other "giants"</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width:&#32;; -webkit-column-width:&#32;; column-width:&#32;;">
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Gigantes">Gigantes</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/220px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="215" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/330px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg/440px-Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2250" data-file-height="2200" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Enkelados_Louvre_CA3662.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a> (left) fighting Enceladus (inscribed retrograde) on an <a href="/wiki/Attica" title="Attica">Attic</a> <a href="/wiki/Red-figure_pottery" title="Red-figure pottery">red-figure</a> dish, c. 550–500&#160;BC (<a href="/wiki/Louvre" title="Louvre">Louvre</a> CA3662).<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Gigantes" class="mw-redirect" title="Gigantes">Gigantes</a> were the offspring of <a href="/wiki/Gaia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaia (mythology)">Gaia</a> (Earth), born from the blood that fell when <a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a> (Sky) was castrated by their <a href="/wiki/Titan_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Titan (mythology)">Titan</a> son <a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a>, who fought the Gigantomachy, their war with the <a href="/wiki/Olympian_gods" class="mw-redirect" title="Olympian gods">Olympian gods</a> for supremacy of the cosmos, they include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alcyoneus" title="Alcyoneus">Alcyoneus</a> (Ἀλκυονεύς), a giant usually considered to be one of the Gigantes, slain by Heracles.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chthonius" title="Chthonius">Chthonius</a> (Χθόνιος).</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Damysus_(Giant)" title="Damysus (Giant)">Damysus</a> (Δάμυσος), the fastest of all the Giants in the Greek mythology.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enceladus_(Giant)" class="mw-redirect" title="Enceladus (Giant)">Enceladus</a> (Ἐγκέλαδος), typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a>, said to be buried under <a href="/wiki/Mount_Etna" title="Mount Etna">Mount Etna</a> in <a href="/wiki/Sicily" title="Sicily">Sicily</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mimas_(Giant)" title="Mimas (Giant)">Mimas</a> (Μίμας), according to <a href="/wiki/Bibliotheca_(Pseudo-Apollodorus)" title="Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)">Apollodorus</a>, he was killed by <a href="/wiki/Hephaestus" title="Hephaestus">Hephaestus</a>, or by others <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> or <a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pallas_(Giant)" title="Pallas (Giant)">Pallas</a> (Πάλλας), according to <a href="/wiki/Bibliotheca_(Pseudo-Apollodorus)" title="Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)">Apollodorus</a>, he was flayed by Athena, who used his skin as a shield.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Polybotes" title="Polybotes">Polybotes</a> (Πολυβώτης), typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Porphyrion" title="Porphyrion">Porphyrion</a> (Πορφυρίων), one of the leaders of the Gigantes, typically slain by <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Giants_(Greek_mythology)#Named_Giants" title="Giants (Greek mythology)">Thoas/Thoon</a> (Θόων), he was killed by the <a href="/wiki/Moirai" title="Moirai">Moirai</a>.
<ul><li><i>For a more complete list of Gigantes see <a href="/wiki/Giants_(Greek_mythology)#Named_Giants" title="Giants (Greek mythology)">Giants (Greek mythology)#Named Giants</a>.</i></li></ul></li></ul>
<h4><span id="Other_.22giants.22"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_&quot;giants&quot;">Other "giants"</span></h4>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aloadae" title="Aloadae">Aloadae</a> (Ἀλῳάδαι), twin giants who attempted to climb to Olympus by piling mountains on top of each other.
<ul><li>Otus or Otos (Ότος)</li>
<li>Ephialtes (Εφιάλτης)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anax" title="Anax">Anax</a> (Αναξ) was a giant of the island of Lade near Miletos in Lydia, Anatolia.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antaeus" title="Antaeus">Antaeus</a> (Ἀνταῖος), a Libyan giant who wrestled all visitors to the death until he was slain by Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antiphates" title="Antiphates">Antiphates</a> (Ἀντιφάτης), the king of the man-eating giants known as Laestrygones which were encountered by Odysseus on his travels.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Argus_Panoptes" title="Argus Panoptes">Argus Panoptes</a> (Ἄργος Πανόπτης), a hundred-eyed giant tasked with guarding over Io</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asterius_(Giant)" class="mw-redirect" title="Asterius (Giant)">Asterius</a> (Αστεριος), a Lydian giant.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cacus" title="Cacus">Cacus</a> (Κακος), a fire-breathing Latin giant slain by Heracles.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cyclopes" title="Cyclopes">Cyclopes</a> (Hesiodic), three one-eyed giants who forged the lightning-bolts of Zeus, Trident of Poseidon and Helmet of Hades
<ul><li>Arges (Ἄργης)</li>
<li>Brontes (Βρόντης)</li>
<li>Steropes (Στερόπης)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cyclopes" title="Cyclopes">Cyclopes</a> (Homeric), a tribe of one-eyed, man-eating giants who herded flocks of sheep on the island of Sicily
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Polyphemus" title="Polyphemus">Polyphemus</a> (Πολύφημος), a Cyclops who briefly captured <a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a> and his men, only to be overcome and blinded by the hero</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Gegenees" title="Gegenees">Gegenees</a> (Γηγενέες), a tribe of six-armed giants fought by the Argonauts on Bear Mountain in Mysia</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Geryon" title="Geryon">Geryon</a> (Γηρυων), a three-bodied giant who dwelt on the sunset isle at the ends of the earth. He was slain by Heracles when the hero arrived to fetch the giant's cattle as one of his twelve labours.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Hekatoncheires" class="mw-redirect" title="Hekatoncheires">Hekatoncheires</a> (Ἑκατόγχειρες), or Centimanes (Latin), the Hundred-Handed Ones, giant gods of violent storms and hurricanes. Three sons of Uranus and Gaia, each with his own distinct characters.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>Briareus (Βριάρεως) or Aigaion (Αἰγαίων), The Vigorous</li>
<li>Cottus (Κόττος), The Furious</li>
<li>Gyges (Γύγης), The Big-Limbed</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Laestrygonians" title="Laestrygonians">Laestrygonians</a> (Λαιστρυγόνες), a tribe of man-eating giants encountered by Odysseus on his travels</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orion_(mythology)" title="Orion (mythology)">Orion</a> (Ὠρίων), a giant huntsman whom Zeus placed among the stars as the <a href="/wiki/Orion_(constellation)" title="Orion (constellation)">constellation of Orion</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Talos" title="Talos">Talos</a> (Τάλως), a giant forged from bronze by Hephaestus, and given by Zeus to his lover Europa as her personal protector</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tityos" title="Tityos">Tityos</a> (Τίτυος), a giant slain by Apollo and Artemis when he attempted to violate their mother Leto.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Typhon" title="Typhon">Typhon</a> (Τυφῶν), a monstrous immortal storm-giant who attempted to launch an attack on <a href="/wiki/Mount_Olympus" title="Mount Olympus">Mount Olympus</a> but was defeated by the Olympians and imprisoned in the pits of Tartarus</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Personified_concepts">Personified concepts</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achlys" title="Achlys">Achlys</a> (Ἀχλύς), spirit of the death-mist, personification of sadness, misery and poison</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adephagia" title="Adephagia">Adephagia</a> (Ἀδηφαγία), spirit of satiety and gluttony</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adikia" title="Adikia">Adikia</a> (Ἀδικία), spirit of injustice and wrongdoing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aergia" title="Aergia">Aergia</a> (Ἀεργία), spirit of idleness, laziness, indolence and sloth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agathodaemon" title="Agathodaemon">Agathodaemon</a> (Ἀγαθοδαίμων), spirit of the <a href="/wiki/Vineyard" title="Vineyard">vineyards</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cereal" title="Cereal">grainfields</a>. Ensuring good <a href="/wiki/Luck" title="Luck">luck</a>, <a href="/wiki/Health" title="Health">health</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Wisdom" title="Wisdom">wisdom</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agon" title="Agon">Agon</a> (Ἀγών), spirit of contest, who possessed an altar at Olympia, site of the Olympic Games.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aidos" title="Aidos">Aidos</a> (Αἰδώς), spirit of modesty, reverence and respect</li>
<li>Aisa (Αἴσα), personification of lot and fate</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alala" title="Alala">Alala</a> (Ἀλαλά), spirit of the war cry</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alastor" title="Alastor">Alastor</a> (Ἀλάστωρ), spirit of blood feuds and vengeance</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aletheia" title="Aletheia">Aletheia</a> (Ἀλήθεια), spirit of truth, truthfulness and sincerity</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Algos" title="Algos">Algea</a> (Ἄλγεα), spirits of pain and suffering
<ul><li>Achos (Ἄχος) "trouble, distress"</li>
<li>Ania (Ἀνία) "ache, anguish"</li>
<li>Lupe (Λύπη) "pain, grief, sadness"</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alke" title="Alke">Alke</a> (Ἀλκή), spirit of prowess and courage (one of the <a href="/wiki/Machai" title="Machai">Machai</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amechania" title="Amechania">Amechania</a> (Ἀμηχανία), spirit of helplessness and want of means</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Amphilogiai" class="mw-redirect" title="Amphilogiai">Amphilogiai</a> (Ἀμφιλογίαι), spirits of disputes, debate, and contention</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anaideia" title="Anaideia">Anaideia</a> (Ἀναίδεια), spirit of ruthlessness, shamelessness, and unforgivingness</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Androktasiai" title="Androktasiai">Androktasiai</a> (Ἀνδροκτασίαι), spirits of battlefield slaughter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Angelia" title="Angelia">Angelia</a> (Ἀγγελία), spirit of messages, tidings and proclamations</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Apate_(deity)" class="mw-redirect" title="Apate (deity)">Apate</a> (Ἀπάτη), spirit of deceit, guile, fraud and deception</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Apheleia" title="Apheleia">Apheleia</a> (Ἀφέλεια), spirit of simplicity</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Arae" title="Arae">Arae</a> (Ἀραί), spirits of curses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arete_(moral_virtue)#Personification" class="mw-redirect" title="Arete (moral virtue)">Arete</a> (Ἀρετή), spirit of virtue, excellence, goodness, and valour</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/At%C3%AB" title="Atë">Atë</a> (Ἄτη), spirit of delusion, infatuation, blind folly, recklessness, and ruin</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bia_(mythology)" title="Bia (mythology)">Bia</a> (Βία "Violence"), the personification of force and raw energy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Caerus" title="Caerus">Caerus</a> (Καιρός), spirit of opportunity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Corus_(mythology)" title="Corus (mythology)">Corus</a> (Κόρος), spirit of surfeit</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deimos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deimos (mythology)">Deimos</a> (Δεῖμος), spirit of fear, dread, and terror</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dikaiosyne" class="mw-redirect" title="Dikaiosyne">Dikaiosyne</a> (Δικαιοσύνη), spirit of justice and righteousness</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dike_(mythology)" title="Dike (mythology)">Dike</a> (Δίκη), spirit of justice, fair judgement, and the rights established by custom and law</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dolos_(mythology)" title="Dolos (mythology)">Dolos</a> (Δόλος), spirit of trickery, cunning deception, craftiness, treachery, and guile</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dysnomia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Dysnomia (mythology)">Dysnomia</a> (Δυσνομία), spirit of lawlessness and poor civil constitution</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dyssebeia" title="Dyssebeia">Dyssebeia</a> (Δυσσέβεια), spirit of impiety</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eirene_(Greek_goddess)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eirene (Greek goddess)">Eirene</a> (Εἰρήνη), goddess of peace</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eiresione" title="Eiresione">Eiresione</a> (Ειρεσιώνη), personification of the olive branch</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ekecheiria" title="Ekecheiria">Ekecheiria</a> (Ἐκεχειρία), spirit of truce, armistice, and the cessation of all hostilities; honoured at the Olympic Games</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eleos" title="Eleos">Eleos</a> (Ἔλεος), spirit of mercy, pity, and compassion</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Elpis" title="Elpis">Elpis</a> (Ἐλπίς), spirit of hope and expectation</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epiphron" title="Epiphron">Epiphron</a> (Ἐπίφρων), spirit of prudence, shrewdness, thoughtfulness, carefulness, and sagacity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eris_(mythology)" title="Eris (mythology)">Eris</a> (Ἔρις), spirit of strife, discord, contention, and rivalry</li></ul>

<li><a href="/wiki/Phthonus" title="Phthonus">Phthonus</a> (Φθόνος), spirit of envy and jealousy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pistis" title="Pistis">Pistis</a> (Πίστις), spirit of trust, honesty, and good faith</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Poine" class="mw-redirect" title="Poine">Poine</a> (Ποίνη), spirit of retribution, vengeance, recompense, punishment, and penalty for the crime of murder and manslaughter</li>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Chthonic_deities"><a href="/wiki/Chthonic" title="Chthonic">Chthonic</a> deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Amphiaraus" title="Amphiaraus">Amphiaraus</a> (Ἀμφιάραος), a seer, and one of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a> who became an oracular spirit of the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Angelos_(Greek_mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Angelos (Greek mythology)">Angelos</a> (Ἄγγελος), a daughter of Zeus and Hera who became an underworld goddess</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ascalaphus" title="Ascalaphus">Askalaphos</a> (Ἀσκάλαφος), the son of Acheron and Orphne who tended the Underworld orchards before being transformed into a screech owl by Demeter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Charon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Charon (mythology)">Charon</a> (Χάρων), ferryman of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cronus" title="Cronus">Cronus</a> (Κρόνος), deposed king of the Titans; after his release from Tartarus he was appointed king of the Island of the Blessed</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Erebus" title="Erebus">Erebos</a> (Ἔρεβος), the primeval god of darkness, his mists encircled the underworld and filled the hollows of the earth</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Erinyes" title="Erinyes">Erinyes</a> (Ἐρινύες), the Furies, goddesses of retribution, known as "The Kindly Ones"
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alecto" title="Alecto">Alecto</a> (Ἀληκτώ), the unceasing one</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tisiphone" title="Tisiphone">Tisiphone</a> (Τισιφόνη), avenger of murder</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Megaera" title="Megaera">Megaera</a> (Μέγαιρα), the jealous one</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hecate" title="Hecate">Hecate</a> (Ἑκάτη), goddess of magic, witchcraft, the night, moon, ghosts, and necromancy</li>
<li>Judges of the Dead
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aeacus" title="Aeacus">Aiakos</a> (Αἰακός), former mortal king of Aegina, guardian of the keys of Hades and judge of the men of Europe</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> (Μίνως), former mortal king of Crete and judge of the final vote</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Rhadamanthus" title="Rhadamanthus">Rhadamanthys</a> (Ῥαδάμανθυς), former mortal lawmaker and judge of the men of Asia</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Keuthonymos" class="mw-redirect" title="Keuthonymos">Keuthonymos</a> (Κευθόνυμος), an Underworld spirit and father of Menoetes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lampads" class="mw-redirect" title="Lampads">Lampades</a> (Λαμπάδες), torch-bearing Underworld nymphs
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Gorgyra" class="mw-redirect" title="Gorgyra">Gorgyra</a> (Γοργύρα)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orphne" title="Orphne">Orphne</a> (Ορφνη), a Lampad nymph of Hades, mother of Askalaphos</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Macaria" title="Macaria">Macaria</a> (Μακαρία), daughter of Hades and goddess of blessed death (not to be confused with the daughter of <a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Melinoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Melinoe">Melinoe</a> (Μελινόη), daughter of Persephone and Zeus who presided over the propitiations offered to the ghosts of the dead</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Menoetius_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Menoetius (mythology)">Menoetes</a> (Μενοίτης), an Underworld spirit who herded the cattle of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nyx_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Nyx (mythology)">Nyx</a> (Νύξ), the primeval goddess of night</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hades_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Hades (mythology)">Hades</a> (¨Αδης) God of underworld and all things beneath the earth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a> (Περσεφόνη), queen of the underworld, wife of Hades and goddess of spring growth</li>
<li>Rivers of the Underworld
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Acheron" title="Acheron">Acheron</a> (Αχέρων), the river of woe</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alpheus_(deity)" title="Alpheus (deity)">Alpheus</a> (Ἀλφειός), the white river</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cocytus" title="Cocytus">Kokytos</a> (Kωκυτός), the river of wailing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eridanos_(river_of_Hades)" title="Eridanos (river of Hades)">Eridanos</a> (Ἠριδανός), the river of amber</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lethe" title="Lethe">Lethe</a> (Λήθη), the river of forgetfulness (its counterpart was the waters of <a href="/wiki/Mnemosyne" title="Mnemosyne">Mnemosyne</a>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phlegethon" title="Phlegethon">Phlegethon</a> (Φλεγέθων), the river of fire</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Styx" title="Styx">Styx</a> (Στύξ), the river of hatred and oaths</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tartarus" title="Tartarus">Tartarus</a> (Τάρταρος), the primeval god of the dark, stormy pit of Hades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thanatos" title="Thanatos">Thanatos</a> (Θάνατος), god of death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Zagreus" title="Zagreus">Zagreus</a> (Ζαγρεύς), an underworld god, possibly a son of Zeus and Persephone</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sea_deities"><a href="/wiki/Greek_sea_gods" title="Greek sea gods">Sea deities</a></span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 35em; -webkit-column-width: 35em; column-width: 35em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Hecatonchires" class="mw-redirect" title="Hecatonchires">Aegaeon</a> (Αιγαίων), god of violent sea storms and ally of the Titans</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphitrite" title="Amphitrite">Amphitrite</a> (Αμφιτρίτη), sea goddess and consort of Poseidon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Benthesikyme" title="Benthesikyme">Benthesikyme</a> (Βενθεσικύμη), daughter of Poseidon, who resided in <a href="/wiki/Ethiopia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ethiopia (mythology)">Ethiopia</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Brizo" title="Brizo">Brizo</a> (Βριζώ), patron goddess of sailors, who sent prophetic dreams</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ceto" title="Ceto">Ceto</a> (Κῆτώ), goddess of the dangers of the ocean and of sea monsters</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cymopoleia" class="mw-redirect" title="Cymopoleia">Cymopoleia</a> (Κυμοπόλεια), a daughter of Poseidon married to the Giant Briareus</li>
<li>Eidothea (Ειδοθέα), prophetic sea nymph and daughter of <a href="/wiki/Proteus" title="Proteus">Proteus</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glaucus" title="Glaucus">Glaucus</a> (Γλαῦκος), the fisherman's sea god and oracle</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Leucothea" title="Leucothea">Leucothea</a> (Λευκοθέα), a sea goddess who aided sailors in distress</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nereid" title="Nereid">Nereides</a> (Νηρηίδες), sea nymphs
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Arethusa_(mythology)" title="Arethusa (mythology)">Arethusa</a> (Αρετούσα), a daughter of <a href="/wiki/Nereus" title="Nereus">Nereus</a> who was transformed into a fountain</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dynamene" title="Dynamene">Dynamene</a> (Δυναμένη), associated with the might and power of great ocean swells</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Galene_(mythology)" title="Galene (mythology)">Galene</a> (Γαλήνη), goddess of calm seas</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Psamathe_(Nereid)" title="Psamathe (Nereid)">Psamathe</a> (Πσαμάθη), goddess of sand beaches</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thetis" title="Thetis">Thetis</a> (Θέτις), leader of the Nereids who presided over the spawning of marine life in the sea</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nereus" title="Nereus">Nereus</a> (Νηρέας), the old man of the sea, and the god of the sea's rich bounty of fish</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nerites_(mythology)" title="Nerites (mythology)">Nerites</a> (Νερίτης), a sea spirit who was transformed into a shell-fish by Aphrodite</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oceanid" class="mw-redirect" title="Oceanid">Oceanides</a> (Ωκεανίδες), sea nymphs, and patronesses of bodies of fresh water
<dl><dd><i>Some notable Oceanides include:</i></dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Idyia" title="Idyia">Idyia</a> (Ίδυια), wife of the Colchian king <a href="/wiki/Aeetes" class="mw-redirect" title="Aeetes">Aeetes</a>, mother of <a href="/wiki/Medea" title="Medea">Medea</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Metis_(mythology)" title="Metis (mythology)">Metis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a>' first wife, whom Zeus impregnated with <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a> and then swallowed.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Styx" title="Styx">Styx</a>, goddess of the river Styx</li></ul>
<dl><dd><i>For a more complete list, see <a href="/wiki/List_of_Oceanids" title="List of Oceanids">List of Oceanids</a></i></dd></dl></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oceanus" title="Oceanus">Oceanus</a> (Ὠκεανός), Titan god of the Earth-encircling river Oceanus (the ocean), the fountain of all the Earth's fresh water</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Potamoi" title="Potamoi">Potamoi</a> (Ποταμοί), Gods of rivers and streams of the earth
<dl><dd><i>Some notable river gods include:</i></dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achelous" title="Achelous">Achelous</a>, the god of the <a href="/wiki/Achelous_River" title="Achelous River">Achelous River</a>, the largest river in Greece, who gave his daughter in marriage to <a href="/wiki/Alcmaeon_(mythology)" title="Alcmaeon (mythology)">Alcmaeon</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alpheus_(deity)" title="Alpheus (deity)">Alpheus</a>, who fell in love with the <a href="/wiki/Nymph" title="Nymph">nymph</a> <a href="/wiki/Arethusa_(mythology)" title="Arethusa (mythology)">Arethusa</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Inachus" title="Inachus">Inachus</a>, the first king of Argos and progenitor of Argive line through his son grandson Argus.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nilus_(mythology)" title="Nilus (mythology)">Nilus</a>, Egyptian river god and the father of numerous daughters that mingled with the descendants of Inachus.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Peneus" title="Peneus">Peneus</a>, river god of Thessaly flowing from the foot of Pindus. He was the father of <a href="/wiki/Daphne" title="Daphne">Daphne</a> and <a href="/wiki/Stilbe" title="Stilbe">Stilbe</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Scamander" title="Scamander">Scamander</a>, who fought on the side of the <a href="/wiki/Troy" title="Troy">Trojans</a> during the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a>.</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Palaemon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Palaemon (mythology)">Palaemon</a> (Παλαίμων), a young sea god who aided sailors in distress</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phorcys" title="Phorcys">Phorcys</a> (Φόρκυς), god of the hidden dangers of the deep</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pontus_(mythology)" title="Pontus (mythology)">Pontos</a> (Πόντος), primeval god of the sea, father of the fish and other sea creatures</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Proteus" title="Proteus">Proteus</a> (Πρωτεύς), a shape-shifting, prophetic old sea god, and the herdsman of Poseidon's seals</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Poseidon" title="Poseidon">Poseidon</a> (Ποσειδῶν), king of the sea and lord of the sea gods; also god of rivers, flood and drought, earthquakes, and horses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sangarius_(mythology)" title="Sangarius (mythology)">Sangarius</a> (Σαγγάριος), a river-god</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Telchines" title="Telchines">Telchines</a> (Τελχινες), sea spirits native to the island of Rhodes; the gods killed them when they turned to evil magic
<ul><li>Actaeus (Ακταίος)</li>
<li>Argyron (Αργυρών)</li>
<li>Atabyrius (Αταβύριος)</li>
<li>Chalcon (Χαλκών)</li>
<li>Chryson (Χρυσών)</li>
<li>Damon (Δαμων) or Demonax (Δημώναξ)</li>
<li>Damnameneus (Δαμναμενεύς)</li>
<li>Dexithea (Δεξιθέα), mother of Euxanthios by <a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a></li>
<li>Lycos (Λύκος) or Lyktos (Λύκτος)</li>
<li>Lysagora (Λυσαγόρα)?</li>
<li>Makelo (Μακελώ)</li>
<li>Megalesius (Μεγαλήσιος)</li>
<li>Mylas (Μύλας)</li>
<li>Nikon (Νίκων)</li>
<li>Ormenos (Ορμενος)</li>
<li>Simon (Σίμων)</li>
<li>Skelmis (Σκελμις)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tethys_(mythology)" title="Tethys (mythology)">Tethys</a> (Τηθύς), Titan goddess of the sources of fresh water, and the mother of the rivers, springs, streams, fountains, and clouds</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thalassa_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Thalassa (mythology)">Thalassa</a> (Θάλασσα), primeval goddess of the sea and consort of Pontos</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thaumas" title="Thaumas">Thaumas</a> (Θαῦμας), god of the wonders of the sea</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thoosa" title="Thoosa">Thoosa</a> (Θόοσα), goddess of swift currents</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Triteia" title="Triteia">Triteia</a> (Τριτεια), daughter of Triton and companion of Ares</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Triton_(mythology)" title="Triton (mythology)">Triton</a> (Τρίτων), fish-tailed son and herald of Poseidon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Triton_(mythology)#Tritons" title="Triton (mythology)">Tritones</a> (Τρίτωνες), fish-tailed spirits in Poseidon's retinue</li></ul>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg/220px-Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="356" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg/330px-Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg/440px-Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg 2x" data-file-width="756" data-file-height="1222" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Neptune_et_Amphitrite.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Poseidon and Amphitrite framed by <a href="/wiki/Erotes_(Mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Erotes (Mythology)">erotes</a> and riding in a <a href="/wiki/Quadriga" title="Quadriga">chariot</a> drawn by <a href="/wiki/Hippocamp" class="mw-redirect" title="Hippocamp">hippocamps</a>; below them are fishermen at work, with nymphs and creatures of the sea in the waters <i>(color-enhanced <a href="/wiki/Roman_mosaic" title="Roman mosaic">Roman-era mosaic</a>)</i></div></div></div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sky_deities">Sky deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aeolus" title="Aeolus">Aeolus</a> (Aiolos) (Αίολος), god of the winds.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aether_(mythology)" title="Aether (mythology)">Aether</a> (Αιθήρ), primeval god of the upper air</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alectrona" class="mw-redirect" title="Alectrona">Alectrona</a> (Αλεκτρονα), solar goddess of the morning or waking up</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anemoi" title="Anemoi">Anemoi</a>, (Άνεμοι), gods of the winds
<ul><li>Aparctias (Απαρκτίας), another name for the north wind (not identified with Boreas)</li>
<li>Apheliotes (Αφηλιώτης), god of the east wind (when Eurus is considered southeast)</li>
<li>Argestes (Αργέστης), another name for the west or northwest wind</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Boreas_(god)" class="mw-redirect" title="Boreas (god)">Boreas</a> (Βορέας), god of the north wind and of winter</li>
<li>Caicias (Καικίας), god of the northeast wind</li>
<li>Circios (Κίρκιος) or Thraskias (Θρασκίας), god of the north-northwest wind</li>
<li>Euronotus (Ευρονότος), god of the southeast wind</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eurus_(named_wind)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eurus (named wind)">Eurus</a> (Εύρος), god of the unlucky east or southeast wind</li>
<li>Lips (Λίψ), god of the southwest wind</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anemoi#South_wind_(Notus)" title="Anemoi">Notus</a> (Νότος) god of the south wind</li>
<li>Skeiron (Σκείρων), god of the northwest wind</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Zephyrus" class="mw-redirect" title="Zephyrus">Zephyrus</a> (Ζέφυρος), god of the west wind</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arke_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Arke (mythology)">Arke</a> (Άρκη), messenger of the Titans and twin sister of Iris</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Astraeus" title="Astraeus">Astraios</a> (Ἀστραῖος), Titan god of stars and planets, and the art of astrology</li>
<li>The Astra Planeti (Αστρα Πλανετοι), gods of the five wandering stars or planets
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Stilbon_(mythology)" title="Stilbon (mythology)">Stilbon</a> (Στιλβών), god of Hermaon, the planet <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(planet)" title="Mercury (planet)">Mercury</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eosphorus" class="mw-redirect" title="Eosphorus">Eosphorus</a> (Ηωσφόρος), god of <a href="/wiki/Venus" title="Venus">Venus</a> the morning star</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hesperus" title="Hesperus">Hesperus</a> (Ἓσπερος), god of Venus the evening star</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pyroeis" title="Pyroeis">Pyroeis</a> (Πυρόεις), god of Areios, the planet <a href="/wiki/Mars" title="Mars">Mars</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phaethon" title="Phaethon">Phaethon</a> (Φαέθων), god of Dios, the planet <a href="/wiki/Jupiter" title="Jupiter">Jupiter</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phaenon" title="Phaenon">Phaenon</a> (Φαίνων), god of Kronion, the planet <a href="/wiki/Saturn" title="Saturn">Saturn</a></li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aurai" class="mw-redirect" title="Aurai">Aurai</a> (Αὖραι), nymphs of the cooling breeze
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aura_(mythology)" title="Aura (mythology)">Aura</a> (Αὖρα), goddess of the breeze and the fresh, cool air of early morning</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chione_(daughter_of_Boreas)" title="Chione (daughter of Boreas)">Chione</a> (Χιόνη), goddess of snow and daughter of Boreas</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eos" title="Eos">Eos</a> (Ἠώς), Titan goddess of the dawn</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ersa" title="Ersa">Ersa</a> (Ἕρση), goddess of the morning dew</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a> (Ἥλιος), Titan god of the sun and guardian of oaths</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hemera" title="Hemera">Hemera</a> (Ημέρα), primeval goddess of the day</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hera" title="Hera">Hera</a> (Ήρα), queen of the gods</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Hesperides" title="Hesperides">Hesperides</a>, (´Εσπερίδες), nymphs of the evening and sunset</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iris_(mythology)" title="Iris (mythology)">Iris</a> (Ίρις), goddess of the rainbow and divine messenger</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Men_(deity)" title="Men (deity)">Men</a> (Μήν), a lunar deity worshiped in the western interior parts of <a href="/wiki/Classical_Anatolia" title="Classical Anatolia">Anatolia</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nephele" title="Nephele">Nephele</a> (Νεφέλη), cloud nymph</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nyx" title="Nyx">Nyx</a>, (Νύξ), goddess of night</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandia" title="Pandia">Pandia</a> (Πανδία), daughter of Selene and Zeus</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Pleiades_(Greek_mythology)" title="Pleiades (Greek mythology)">Pleiades</a> (Πλειάδες), goddesses of the star cluster <a href="/wiki/Pleiades" title="Pleiades">Pleiades</a> and were associated with rain
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alcyone_(Pleiades)" class="mw-redirect" title="Alcyone (Pleiades)">Alcyone</a> (Αλκυόνη)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sterope_(Pleiad)" title="Sterope (Pleiad)">Sterope</a> (Στερόπη)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Celaeno" title="Celaeno">Celaeno</a> (Κελαινώ)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Electra_(Pleiad)" title="Electra (Pleiad)">Electra</a> (Ηλέκτρα)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Maia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Maia (mythology)">Maia</a> (Μαία)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Merope_(Pleiades)" class="mw-redirect" title="Merope (Pleiades)">Merope</a> (Μερώπη)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Taygete" title="Taygete">Taygete</a> (Ταϋγέτη)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sabazios" title="Sabazios">Sabazios</a> (Σαβάζιος), the nomadic horseman and <a href="/wiki/Sky_father" title="Sky father">sky father</a> god of the <a href="/wiki/Phrygians" title="Phrygians">Phrygians</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thracians" title="Thracians">Thracians</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Selene" title="Selene">Selene</a> (Σελήνη), Titan goddess of the moon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Uranus_(mythology)" title="Uranus (mythology)">Uranus</a> (Ουρανός), primeval god of the heavens</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</a> (Ζεύς), King of Heaven and god of the sky, clouds, thunder, and lightning</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rustic_deities">Rustic deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aetna_(nymph)" title="Aetna (nymph)">Aetna</a> (Αἴτνη), goddess of the volcanic <a href="/wiki/Mount_Etna" title="Mount Etna">Mount Etna</a> in Sicily</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphictyonis" title="Amphictyonis">Amphictyonis</a> (Αμφικτυονίς), goddess of wine and friendship between nations, a local form of Demeter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anthousai" title="Anthousai">Anthousai</a> (Ανθούσαι), flower <a href="/wiki/Nymphs" class="mw-redirect" title="Nymphs">nymphs</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aristaeus" title="Aristaeus">Aristaeus</a> (Ἀρισταῖος), god of bee-keeping, cheese-making, herding, olive-growing, and hunting</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Attis" title="Attis">Attis</a> (Άττις), vegetation god and consort of Cybele</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Britomartis" title="Britomartis">Britomartis</a> (Βριτόμαρτις), Cretan goddess of hunting and nets used for fishing, fowling and the hunting of small game</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cabeiri" title="Cabeiri">Cabeiri</a> (Κάβειροι), gods or spirits who presided over the Mysteries of the islands of Lemnos and Samothrace
<ul><li>Aitnaios (Αιτναιος)</li>
<li>Alkon (Αλκων)</li>
<li>Eurymedon (Ευρυμεδών)</li>
<li>Onnes (Όννης)</li>
<li>Tonnes (Τόννης)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chloris#Chloris_(Nymph)" title="Chloris">Chloris</a> (Χλωρίς), minor flower nymph and wife of Zephyrus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Comus" title="Comus">Comus</a> (Κόμος), god of revelry, merrymaking, and festivity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Corymbus" class="mw-redirect" title="Corymbus">Corymbus</a> (Κόρυμβος), god of the fruit of the ivy</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Korybantes" title="Korybantes">Curetes</a> (Κουρέτες), guardians of infant Zeus on Mount Ida, barely distinguished from the Dactyls and the Corybantes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cybele" title="Cybele">Cybele</a> (Κυβέλη), a Phrygian mountain goddess</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Dactyl_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Dactyl (mythology)">Dactyls</a> (Δάκτυλοι) "fingers", minor deities originally representing fingers of a hand
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Acmon_(Dactyl)" title="Acmon (Dactyl)">Acmon</a> (Ακμών)</li>
<li>Damnameneus (Δαμναμενεύς)</li>
<li>Delas (Δήλας)</li>
<li>Epimedes (Επιμήδης)</li>
<li>Heracles (not to be confused with the hero <a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a>)</li>
<li>Iasios (Ιάσιος)</li>
<li>Kelmis (Κελμις)</li>
<li>Skythes (Σκύθης)</li>
<li>companions of Cybele
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Titias" title="Titias">Titias</a> (Τιτίας)</li>
<li>Cyllenus (Κύλληνος)</li></ul></li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a> (Διόνυσος), god of wine, drunken orgies, and wild vegetation</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dryad" title="Dryad">Dryades</a> (Δρυάδες), tree and forest nymphs</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Gaia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaia (mythology)">Gaia</a> (Γαία), primeval goddess of the earth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epimeliad" title="Epimeliad">Epimeliades</a> (Επιμελίδες), nymphs of highland pastures and protectors of sheep flocks</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hamadryad" title="Hamadryad">Hamadryades</a> (Αμαδρυάδες), oak tree dryades</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hecaterus" title="Hecaterus">Hecaterus</a> (Ηεκατερος), minor god of the <i>hekateris</i> — a rustic dance of quickly moving hands — and perhaps of the skill of hands in general</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hermes" title="Hermes">Hermes</a> (Ερμής), god of herds and flocks, of roads and boundary stones, and the god of thieves.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Korybantes" title="Korybantes">Korybantes</a> (Κορύβαντες), the crested dancers who worshipped Cybele
<ul><li>Damneus (Δαμνεύς) "the one who tames(?)"</li>
<li>Idaios (Ιδαίος) "of Mount Ida"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Kyrbas" title="Kyrbas">Kyrbas</a> (Κύρβας), whose name is probably a variant of Korybas, singular for "Korybantes"</li>
<li>Okythoos (Ωκύθοος) "the one running swiftly"</li>
<li>Prymneus (Πρυμνεύς) "of lower areas(?)"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pyrrhichos" title="Pyrrhichos">Pyrrhichos</a> (Πυρῥιχος), god of the rustic dance</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ma_(goddess)" title="Ma (goddess)">Ma</a>, a local goddess at <a href="/wiki/Comana_(Cappadocia)" title="Comana (Cappadocia)">Comana</a> in <a href="/wiki/Cappadocia" title="Cappadocia">Cappadocia</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Maenad" title="Maenad">Maenades</a> (μαινάδες), crazed nymphs in the retinue of Dionysus
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Methe" title="Methe">Methe</a> (Μέθη), nymph of drunkenness</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Meliae" title="Meliae">Meliae</a> (Μελίαι), nymphs of honey and the ash tree</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Naiad" title="Naiad">Naiades</a> (Ναιάδες), fresh water nymphs
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Daphne" title="Daphne">Daphne</a> (Δάφνη)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Metope_(mythology)" title="Metope (mythology)">Metope</a> (Μετώπη)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Minthe" title="Minthe">Minthe</a> (Μίνθη)</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Nymphai_Hyperboreioi" title="Nymphai Hyperboreioi">Nymphai Hyperboreioi</a> (Νύμφαι Υπερβόρειοι), who presided over aspects of archery
<ul><li>Hekaerge (Εκαέργη), represented distancing</li>
<li>Loxo (Λοξώ), represented trajectory</li>
<li>Oupis (Ουπις), represented aim</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oread" title="Oread">Oreades</a> (Ὀρεάδες), mountain nymphs
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Adrasteia" title="Adrasteia">Adrasteia</a> (Αδράστεια), a nursemaid of the infant Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Echo_(mythology)" title="Echo (mythology)">Echo</a> (Ηχώ), a nymph cursed never to speak except to repeat the words of others</li></ul></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Ourea" title="Ourea">Ourea</a> (Ούρος), primeval gods of mountains</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Palici" title="Palici">Palici</a> (Παλικοί), a pair of rustic gods who presided over the geysers and thermal springs in Sicily</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pan_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pan (mythology)">Pan</a> (Πάν), god of shepherds, pastures, and fertility</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Potamoi" title="Potamoi">Potamoi</a> (Ποταμοί), river gods
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achelous" title="Achelous">Achelous</a> (Αχέλους)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Acis" class="mw-redirect" title="Acis">Acis</a> (Άκις)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alpheus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Alpheus (mythology)">Alpheus</a> (Αλφειός)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asopus" title="Asopus">Asopus</a> (Ασωπός)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cladeus" class="mw-redirect" title="Cladeus">Cladeus</a> (Κλάδεος)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eurotas" title="Eurotas">Eurotas</a> (Ευρώτας)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Nilus_(mythology)" title="Nilus (mythology)">Nilus</a> (Νείλος)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Peneus" title="Peneus">Peneus</a> (Πηνειός)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Scamander" title="Scamander">Scamander</a> (Σκάμανδρος)</li></ul></li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><i>For a more complete list, see <a href="/wiki/Potamoi#List_of_potamoi" title="Potamoi">Potamoi#List of potamoi</a></i></dd></dl></dd></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Priapus" title="Priapus">Priapus</a> (Πρίαπος), god of garden fertility</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Satyr" title="Satyr">Satyrs</a> (Σάτυροι) / <a href="/wiki/Satyress" title="Satyress">Satyress</a>, rustic fertility spirits
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Krotos" title="Krotos">Krotos</a> (Κρότος), a great hunter and musician who kept the company of the Muses on Mount Helicon</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Silenus" title="Silenus">Silenus</a> (Σειληνός), an old rustic god of the dance of the wine-press</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Telete" title="Telete">Telete</a> (Τελέτη), goddess of initiation into the Bacchic orgies</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Zagreus" title="Zagreus">Zagreus</a> (Ζαγρεύς), in the Orphic mysteries, the first incarnation of Dionysus</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Agricultural_deities">Agricultural deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Adonis" title="Adonis">Adonis</a> (Άδωνις), a <a href="/wiki/Life-death-rebirth_deity" class="mw-redirect" title="Life-death-rebirth deity">life-death-rebirth deity</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aphaea" title="Aphaea">Aphaea</a> (Αφαία), minor goddess of agriculture and fertility</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cyamites" title="Cyamites">Cyamites</a> (Κυαμίτης), demi-god of the bean</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Demeter" title="Demeter">Demeter</a> (Δημήτηρ), goddess of fertility, agriculture, grain, and harvest</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Despoina" title="Despoina">Despoina</a> (Δέσποινη), daughter of Poseidon and Demeter, goddess of mysteries in <a href="/wiki/Arcadia_(ancient_region)" class="mw-redirect" title="Arcadia (ancient region)">Arcadia</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a> (Διόνυσος), god of viticulture and wine</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eunostus" title="Eunostus">Eunostus</a> (Εύνοστος), goddess of the flour mill</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Persephone" title="Persephone">Persephone</a> (Περσεφόνη), queen of the underworld, wife of Hades and goddess of spring growth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Philomelus" title="Philomelus">Philomelus</a> (Φιλόμελος), agricultural demi-god inventor of the wagon and the plough</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Plutus" title="Plutus">Plutus</a> (Πλοῦτος), god of wealth, including agricultural wealth, son of Demeter</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Triptolemus" title="Triptolemus">Triptolemus</a> (Τριπτόλεμος), god of farming and agriculture, he brought agriculture to Greece</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Health_deities">Health deities</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a> (Ἀπόλλων), god of disease and healing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asclepius" title="Asclepius">Asclepius</a> (Ασκληπιός), god of medicine</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aceso" title="Aceso">Aceso</a> (Ἀκεσώ), goddess of the healing of wounds and the curing of illnesses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aegle_(mythology)" title="Aegle (mythology)">Aegle</a> (Αἴγλη), goddess of radiant good health</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chiron" title="Chiron">Chiron</a> (Χείρων). god of healing (up for debate if it is a god)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epione" title="Epione">Epione</a> (Ἠπιόνη), goddess of the soothing of pain</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hygieia" title="Hygieia">Hygieia</a> (Ὑγεία), goddess of cleanliness and good health</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iaso" title="Iaso">Iaso</a> (Ἰασώ), goddess of cures, remedies, and modes of healing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Paean_(god)" title="Paean (god)">Paean</a> (Παιάν), physician of the gods</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Panacea" title="Panacea">Panacea</a> (Πανάκεια), goddess of healing</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Telesphorus_(mythology)" title="Telesphorus (mythology)">Telesphorus</a> (Τελεσφόρος), demi-god of convalescence, who "brought to fulfillment" recuperation from illness or injury</li></ul>
</div>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_deities">Other deities</span></h3>

<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Acratopotes" title="Acratopotes">Acratopotes</a> (Ἀκρατοπότης), god of unmixed wine</li>

<li><a href="/wiki/Thalia_(Grace)" title="Thalia (Grace)">Thalia</a> (Θάλεια), goddess of festive celebrations and rich and luxurious banquets</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hegemone" title="Hegemone">Hegemone</a> (Ηγεμόνη) "mastery"</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antheia" title="Antheia">Antheia</a> (Άνθεια), goddess of flowers and flowery wreaths</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pasithea" title="Pasithea">Pasithea</a> (Πασιθέα), goddess of rest and relaxation</li>
<li>Cleta (Κλήτα) "the glorious"</li>
<li>Phaenna (Φαέννα) "the shining"</li>
<li>Eudaimonia (Ευδαιμονία) "happiness"</li>
<li>Euthymia (Ευθυμία) "good mood"</li>
<li>Calleis (Καλλείς) "beauty"</li>
<li>Paidia (Παιδία) "play, amusement"</li>
<li>Pandaisia (Πανδαισία) "banquet for everyone"</li>
<li>Pannychis (Παννυχίς) "all-night (festivity)"</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ceraon" title="Ceraon">Ceraon</a> (Κεραων), demi-god of the meal, specifically the mixing of wine</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chrysus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Chrysus (mythology)">Chrysus</a> (Χρύσος), spirit of gold</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Circe" title="Circe">Circe</a> (Κίρκη), goddess-witch of Aeaea</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Daemones_Ceramici" title="Daemones Ceramici">Daemones Ceramici</a> (Δαίμονες Κεραμικοί), five malevolent spirits who plagued the craftsman potter
<ul><li>Syntribos (Σύντριβος), the shatterer</li>
<li>Smaragos (Σμάραγος), the smasher</li>
<li>Asbetos (Ασβετος), the charrer</li>
<li>Sabaktes (Σαβάκτης), the destroyer</li>
<li>Omodamos (Ωμόδαμος), crudebake</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deipneus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deipneus (mythology)">Deipneus</a> (Δειπνεύς), demi-god of the preparation of meals, specifically the making of bread</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eileithyia" title="Eileithyia">Eileithyia</a> (Εἰλείθυια), goddess of childbirth</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enyalius" title="Enyalius">Enyalius</a> (Ενυάλιος), minor god of war</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Enyo" title="Enyo">Enyo</a> (Ἐνυώ), goddess of destructive war</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epidotes" title="Epidotes">Epidotes</a> (Ἐπιδώτης), a divinity who was worshipped at <a href="/wiki/Lacedaemon" class="mw-redirect" title="Lacedaemon">Lacedaemon</a><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glycon" title="Glycon">Glycon</a> (Γλύκων), a snake god</li>

<li>The <a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Horae</a> (Ώρες), The Hours, the goddesses of natural order
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Eunomia_(goddess)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eunomia (goddess)">Eunomia</a> (Ευνομία), spirit of good order, and springtime goddess of green pastures</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dike_(mythology)" title="Dike (mythology)">Dike</a> (Δίκη), spirit of justice, may have represented springtime growth</li>

<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Thallo" class="mw-redirect" title="Thallo">Thallo</a> (Θαλλώ), goddess of spring buds and shoots, identified with Eirene</li>

<li><a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Karpo</a> (Καρπώ), goddess of the fruits of the earth</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of welfare
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Pherousa" class="mw-redirect" title="Pherousa">Pherousa</a> (Φέρουσα) "the bringer"</li>
