<li><a href="/wiki/Horae" title="Horae">Orthosie</a> (Ορθοσίη) "prosperity"</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of the natural portions of time and the times of day
<ul><li>Auge (Αυγή), first light of the morning</li>
<li>Anatole (Ανατολή) or Anatolia (Ανατολία), sunrise</li>
<li>Mousika or Musica (Μουσική), the morning hour of music and study</li>
<li>Gymnastika, Gymnastica (Γυμναστίκή) or Gymnasia (Γυμνασία), the morning hour of gymnastics/exercise</li>
<li>Nymphe (Νυμφή), the morning hour of ablutions (bathing, washing)</li>
<li>Mesembria (Μεσημβρία), noon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sponde" title="Sponde">Sponde</a> (Σπονδή), libations poured after lunch</li>
<li>Elete, prayer, the first of the afternoon work hours</li>
<li>Akte, Acte (Ακτή) or Cypris (Κυπρίς), eating and pleasure, the second of the afternoon work hours</li>
<li>Hesperis (Έσπερίς), evening</li>
<li>Dysis (Δύσις), sunset</li>
<li>Arktos (Άρκτος), night sky, constellation</li></ul></li>
<li>The goddesses of seasons of the year
<ul><li>Eiar (Είαρ), spring</li>
<li>Theros (Θέρος), summer</li>
<li>Pthinoporon (Φθινόπωρον), autumn</li>
<li>Cheimon (Χειμών), winter</li></ul></li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hymenaios" class="mw-redirect" title="Hymenaios">Hymenaios</a> (Ὑμέναιος), god of marriage and marriage feasts</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ichnaea" title="Ichnaea">Ichnaea</a> (Ιχναία), goddess of tracking</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iynx" title="Iynx">Iynx</a> (Ιύνξ), goddess of the love charm</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Matton_(mythology)" title="Matton (mythology)">Matton</a> (Μάττων), demi-god of the meal, specifically the kneading of dough</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mene_(goddess)" title="Mene (goddess)">Mene</a>, goddess of the months</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Muse" class="mw-redirect" title="Muse">Muses</a> (Μούσαι), goddesses of music, song and dance, and the source of inspiration to poets
<ul><li>Titan Muses, daughters of <a href="/wiki/Uranus" title="Uranus">Uranus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gaia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaia (mythology)">Gaia</a>

<li><a href="/wiki/Thelxinoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Thelxinoe">Thelxinoe</a> (Θελξινόη), muse "charmer of minds"</li></ul></li>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Mortals">Mortals</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Deified_mortals">Deified mortals</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀχιλλεύς</span>), hero of the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeacus" title="Aeacus">Aiakos</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Αἰακός</span>), a king of Aegina, appointed as a Judge of the Dead in the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeolus" title="Aeolus">Aeolus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Αἴολος</span>), a king of Thessaly, made the immortal king of all the winds by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alabandus" title="Alabandus">Alabandus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀλάβανδος</span>), he was the founder of the town of <a href="/wiki/Alabanda" title="Alabanda">Alabanda</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphiaraus" title="Amphiaraus">Amphiaraus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀμφιάραος</span>), a hero of the war of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a> who became an oracular spirit of the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a> (Αριάδνη), a Cretan princess who became the immortal wife of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aristaeus" title="Aristaeus">Aristaeus</a> (Ἀρισταῖος), a Thessalian hero, his inventions saw him immortalised as the god of bee-keeping, cheese-making, herding, olive-growing, and hunting</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asclepius" title="Asclepius">Asclepius</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἀσκληπιός</span>), a Thessalian physician who was struck down by Zeus, to be later recovered by his father Apollo</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Attis" title="Attis">Attis</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἄττις</span>), a consort of Cybele, granted immortality as one of her attendants</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bolina" title="Bolina">Bolina</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Βολίνα</span>), a mortal woman transformed into an immortal nymph by Apollo</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Dioscuri" class="mw-redirect" title="Dioscuri">Dioscuri</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Διόσκουροι</span>), divine twins
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Castor_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Castor (mythology)">Castor</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Κάστωρ</span>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Castor_and_Pollux" title="Castor and Pollux">Pollux</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Πολυδεύκης</span>)</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Endymion_(mythology)" title="Endymion (mythology)">Endymion</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἐνδυμίων</span>), lover of Selene, granted eternal sleep so as never to age or die</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ganymede_(mythology)" title="Ganymede (mythology)">Ganymede</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Γανυμήδης</span>), a handsome Trojan prince, abducted by Zeus and made cup-bearer of the gods</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glaucus" title="Glaucus">Glaucus</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Γλαῦκος</span>), the fisherman's sea god, made immortal after eating a magical herb</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hemithea_(mythology)" title="Hemithea (mythology)">Hemithea</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἡμιθέα</span>) and Parthenos (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Παρθένος</span>), princesses of the Island of <a href="/wiki/Naxos_(island)" class="mw-redirect" title="Naxos (island)">Naxos</a> who leapt into the sea to escape their father's wrath; Apollo transformed them into demi-goddesses</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἡρακλῆς</span>), ascended hero</li></ul>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/220px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="213" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/330px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg/440px-Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1905" data-file-height="1845" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Athena_Herakles_Staatliche_Antikensammlungen_2648.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Athena pouring a drink for Heracles, who wears the skin of the <a href="/wiki/Nemean_Lion" class="mw-redirect" title="Nemean Lion">Nemean Lion</a></div></div></div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Ino_(Greek_mythology)" title="Ino (Greek mythology)">Ino</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἰνώ</span>), a Theban princess who became the sea goddess Leucothea</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lampsace" title="Lampsace">Lampsace</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Λαμψάκη</span>), a semi-historical Bebrycian princess honored as goddess for her assistance to the Greeks</li>
<li>The Leucippides (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Λευκιππίδες</span>), wives of the Dioscuri
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Phoebe_(Leucippides)" class="mw-redirect" title="Phoebe (Leucippides)">Phoebe</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Φοίβη</span>), wife of Pollux</li>
<li>Hilaera (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ἱλάειρα</span>), wife of Castor</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Μίνως</span>), a king of Crete, appointed as a Judge of the Dead in the Underworld after his death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orithyia_(Athenian)" class="mw-redirect" title="Orithyia (Athenian)">Orithyia</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ὠρείθυια</span>), an Athenian princess abducted by Boreas and made the goddess of cold, gusty mountain winds</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Palaemon_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Palaemon (mythology)">Palaemon</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Παλαίμων</span>), a Theban prince, made into a sea god along with his mother, Ino</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Philoctetes" title="Philoctetes">Philoctetes</a> (<a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient Greek language">Ancient Greek</a>: <span lang="grc">Φιλοκτήτης</span>), was the son of King <a href="/wiki/Poeas" title="Poeas">Poeas</a> of <a href="/wiki/Meliboea" title="Meliboea">Meliboea</a> in <a href="/wiki/Thessaly" title="Thessaly">Thessaly</a>. He was a famous archer, fought at the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phylonoe" class="mw-redirect" title="Phylonoe">Phylonoe</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Φυλονόη</span>), daughter of <a href="/wiki/Tyndareus" title="Tyndareus">Tyndareus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leda_(mythology)" title="Leda (mythology)">Leda</a>, made immortal by Artemis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Psyche_(mythology)" title="Psyche (mythology)">Psyche</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Ψυχή</span>), goddess of the soul</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Σεμελη</span>), mortal mother of <a href="/wiki/Dionysus" title="Dionysus">Dionysus</a>, who later was made the goddess Thyone (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Θυωνη</span>)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tenes" title="Tenes">Tenes</a> (<span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek (to 1453) language text">Τέννης</span>), was a hero of the island of <a href="/wiki/Tenedos" title="Tenedos">Tenedos</a></li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Heroes">Heroes</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Abderus" title="Abderus">Abderus</a>, aided Heracles during his eighth labour and was killed by the <a href="/wiki/Mares_of_Diomedes" title="Mares of Diomedes">Mares of Diomedes</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a> (Αχιλλεύς or Αχιλλέας), hero of the <a href="/wiki/Trojan_War" title="Trojan War">Trojan War</a> and a central character in <a href="/wiki/Homer" title="Homer">Homer</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Iliad" title="Iliad">Iliad</a></i></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeneas" title="Aeneas">Aeneas</a> (Αινείας), a hero of the Trojan War and progenitor of the Roman people</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ajax_the_Great" title="Ajax the Great">Ajax the Great</a> (Αίας ο Μέγας), a hero of the Trojan War and king of <a href="/wiki/Salamis_Island" title="Salamis Island">Salamis</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ajax_the_Lesser" title="Ajax the Lesser">Ajax the Lesser</a> (Αίας ο Μικρός), a hero of the Trojan War and leader of the <a href="/wiki/Locrians" title="Locrians">Locrian</a> army</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphitryon" title="Amphitryon">Amphitryon</a> (Αμφιτρύων), Theban general who rescued Thebes from the <a href="/wiki/Teumessian_fox" title="Teumessian fox">Teumessian fox</a>; his wife was Alcmene, mother of Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antilochus" title="Antilochus">Antilochus</a> (Ἀντίλοχος), Son of Nestor sacrificed himself to save his father in the Trojan War along with other deeds of valor</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bellerophon" title="Bellerophon">Bellerophon</a> (Βελλεροφῶν), hero who slew the <a href="/wiki/Chimera_(mythology)" title="Chimera (mythology)">Chimera</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bouzyges" title="Bouzyges">Bouzyges</a>, a hero credited with inventing agricultural practices such as yoking oxen to a plough</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Castor_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Castor (mythology)">Castor</a>, the mortal Dioscuri twin; after Castor's death, his immortal brother Pollux shared his divinity with him in order that they might remain together</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chrysippus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Chrysippus (mythology)">Chrysippus</a> (Χρύσιππος), a divine hero of Elis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Daedalus" title="Daedalus">Daedalus</a> (Δαίδαλος), creator of the <a href="/wiki/Labyrinth" title="Labyrinth">labyrinth</a> and great inventor, until King <a href="/wiki/Minos" title="Minos">Minos</a> trapped him in his own creation.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Diomedes" title="Diomedes">Diomedes</a> (Διομήδης), a king of Argos and hero of the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eleusis_(mythology)" title="Eleusis (mythology)">Eleusis</a> (Ἐλευσῖνι or Ἐλευσῖνα), eponymous hero of the town of <a href="/wiki/Eleusis" title="Eleusis">Eleusis</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eunostus_(hero)" title="Eunostus (hero)">Eunostus</a>, a Boeotian hero</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ganymede_(mythology)" title="Ganymede (mythology)">Ganymede</a> (Γανυμήδης), Trojan hero and lover of Zeus, who was given immortality and appointed cup-bearer to the gods</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hector" title="Hector">Hector</a> (Ἕκτωρ), hero of the Trojan War and champion of the Trojan people</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Icarus" title="Icarus">Icarus</a> (Ἴκαρος), the son of the master craftsman <a href="/wiki/Daedalus" title="Daedalus">Daedalus</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iolaus" title="Iolaus">Iolaus</a> (Ἰόλαος), nephew of <a href="/wiki/Heracles" title="Heracles">Heracles</a> who aided his uncle in one of his Labors</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Jason" title="Jason">Jason</a> (Ἰάσων), leader of the Argonauts</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Meleager" title="Meleager">Meleager</a> (Μελέαγρος), a hero who sailed with the Argonauts and killed the Calydonian Boar</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Odysseus" title="Odysseus">Odysseus</a> (Ὀδυσσεύς or Ὀδυσεύς), a hero and king of Ithaca whose adventures are the subject of Homer's <i><a href="/wiki/Odyssey" title="Odyssey">Odyssey</a></i>; he also played a key role during the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orpheus" title="Orpheus">Orpheus</a> (Ὀρφεύς), a legendary musician and poet who attempted to retrieve his dead wife from the Underworld</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandion_(hero)" title="Pandion (hero)">Pandion</a> (Πανδίων), the eponymous hero of the <a href="/wiki/Phyle" title="Phyle">Attic tribe</a> Pandionis, usually assumed to be one of the legendary Athenian kings <a href="/wiki/Pandion_I" title="Pandion I">Pandion I</a> or <a href="/wiki/Pandion_II" title="Pandion II">Pandion II</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Perseus_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Perseus (mythology)">Perseus</a> (Περσεύς), son of Zeus and the founder-king of Mycenae and slayer of the Gorgon Medusa</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Theseus" title="Theseus">Theseus</a> (Θησεύς), son of Poseidon and a king of Athens and slayer of the <a href="/wiki/Minotaur" title="Minotaur">Minotaur</a></li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Notable_women">Notable women</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Alcestis" title="Alcestis">Alcestis</a> (Άλκηστις), daughter of Pelias and wife of Admetus, who was known for her devotion to her husband</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amymone" title="Amymone">Amymone</a>, the one daughter of Danaus who refused to murder her husband, thus escaping her sisters' punishment</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andromache" title="Andromache">Andromache</a> (Ανδρομάχη), wife of Hector</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Andromeda_(mythology)" title="Andromeda (mythology)">Andromeda</a> (Ανδρομέδα), wife of Perseus, who was placed among the constellations after her death</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antigone" title="Antigone">Antigone</a> (Αντιγόνη), daughter of Oedipus and Jocasta</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arachne" title="Arachne">Arachne</a> (Αράχνη), a skilled weaver, transformed by Athena into a spider for her blasphemy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ariadne" title="Ariadne">Ariadne</a> (Αριάδνη), daughter of Minos, king of Crete, who aided Theseus in overcoming the Minotaur and became the wife of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Atalanta" title="Atalanta">Atalanta</a> (Αταλάντη), fleet-footed heroine who participated in the Calydonian Boar hunt and the quest for the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Fleece" title="Golden Fleece">Golden Fleece</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Briseis" title="Briseis">Briseis</a>, a princess of <a href="/wiki/Lyrnessus" title="Lyrnessus">Lyrnessus</a>, taken by Achilles as a war prize</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Caeneus" title="Caeneus">Caeneus</a>, formerly Caenis, a woman who was transformed into a man and became a mighty warrior</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cassandra" title="Cassandra">Cassandra</a>, a princess of Troy cursed to see the future but never to be believed</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cassiopeia_(Queen_of_Aethiopia)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cassiopeia (Queen of Aethiopia)">Cassiopeia</a> (Κασσιόπεια), queen of <a href="/wiki/Ethiopia_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ethiopia (mythology)">Æthiopia</a> and mother of <a href="/wiki/Andromeda_(mythology)" title="Andromeda (mythology)">Andromeda</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Clytemnestra" title="Clytemnestra">Clytemnestra</a>, sister of Helen and unfaithful wife of Agamemnon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Dana%C3%AB" title="Danaë">Danaë</a>, the mother of Perseus by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Deianeira" class="mw-redirect" title="Deianeira">Deianeira</a>, the third wife and unwitting killer of Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Electra" title="Electra">Electra</a>, daughter of Agamemnon and Clytemnestra, she aided her brother Orestes in plotting revenge against their mother for the murder of their father</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Europa_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Europa (mythology)">Europa</a>, a Phoenician woman, abducted by Zeus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hecuba" title="Hecuba">Hecuba</a> (Ἑκάβη), wife of Priam, king of Troy, and mother of nineteen of his children</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Helen_of_Troy" title="Helen of Troy">Helen</a>, daughter of Zeus and Leda, whose abduction brought about the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hermione_(mythology)" title="Hermione (mythology)">Hermione</a> (Ἑρμιόνη), daughter of Menelaus and Helen; wife of Neoptolemus, and later Orestes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iphigenia" title="Iphigenia">Iphigenia</a>, daughter of Agamemnon and Clytemnestra; Agamemnon sacrificed her to Artemis in order to appease the goddess</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ismene" title="Ismene">Ismene</a>, sister of Antigone</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Jocasta" title="Jocasta">Jocasta</a>, mother and wife of Oedipus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Medea" title="Medea">Medea</a>, a sorceress and wife of Jason, who killed her own children to punish Jason for his infidelity</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Medusa" title="Medusa">Medusa</a>, a mortal woman transformed into a hideous gorgon by Athena</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Niobe" title="Niobe">Niobe</a>, a daughter of Tantalus who declared herself to be superior to Leto, causing Artemis and Apollo to kill her fourteen children</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandora" title="Pandora">Pandora</a>, the first woman</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Penelope" title="Penelope">Penelope</a>, loyal wife of Odysseus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Phaedra_(mythology)" title="Phaedra (mythology)">Phaedra</a>, daughter of Minos and wife of Theseus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Polyxena" title="Polyxena">Polyxena</a>, the youngest daughter of Priam, sacrificed to the ghost of Achilles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Semele" title="Semele">Semele</a>, mortal mother of Dionysus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thrace_(mythology)" title="Thrace (mythology)">Thrace</a>, the daughter of Oceanus and Parthenope, and sister of Europa</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kings">Kings</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Abas_(son_of_Lynceus)" title="Abas (son of Lynceus)">Abas</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Argos,_Peloponnese" title="Argos, Peloponnese">Argos</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Acastus" title="Acastus">Acastus</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Iolcus" title="Iolcus">Iolcus</a> who sailed with the <a href="/wiki/Argonauts" title="Argonauts">Argonauts</a> and participated in the <a href="/wiki/Calydonian_Boar" title="Calydonian Boar">Calydonian Boar</a> hunt</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Acrisius" title="Acrisius">Acrisius</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Argos,_Peloponnese" title="Argos, Peloponnese">Argos</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Actaeus" title="Actaeus">Actaeus</a>, first king of <a href="/wiki/Attica" title="Attica">Attica</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Admetus" title="Admetus">Admetus</a> (Άδμητος), a king of <a href="/wiki/Pherae" title="Pherae">Pherae</a> who sailed with the Argonauts and participated in the Calydonian Boar hunt</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adrastus" title="Adrastus">Adrastus</a> (Άδραστος), a king of Argos and one of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeacus" title="Aeacus">Aeacus</a> (Αιακός), a king of the island of <a href="/wiki/Aegina" title="Aegina">Aegina</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Saronic_Gulf" title="Saronic Gulf">Saronic Gulf</a>; after he died, he became one of the three judges of the dead in the Underworld</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ae%C3%ABtes" title="Aeëtes">Aeëtes</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Colchis" title="Colchis">Colchis</a> and father of Medea</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aegeus" title="Aegeus">Aegeus</a> (Αιγεύς), a king of <a href="/wiki/Athens" title="Athens">Athens</a> and father of Theseus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aegimius" title="Aegimius">Aegimius</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Thessaly" title="Thessaly">Thessaly</a> and progenitor of the <a href="/wiki/Dorians" title="Dorians">Dorians</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aegisthus" title="Aegisthus">Aegisthus</a> (Αίγισθος), lover of Clytemnestra, with whom he plotted to murder Agamemnon and seized the kingship of <a href="/wiki/Mycenae" title="Mycenae">Mycenae</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aegyptus" title="Aegyptus">Aegyptus</a> (Αίγυπτος), a king of <a href="/wiki/Egypt" title="Egypt">Egypt</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aeson" title="Aeson">Aeson</a>, father of Jason and rightful king of Iolcus, whose throne was usurped by his half-brother Pelias</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aethlius" title="Aethlius">Aëthlius</a>, first king of <a href="/wiki/Elis" class="mw-redirect" title="Elis">Elis</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aetolus" class="mw-redirect" title="Aetolus">Aetolus</a> (Αιτωλός), a king of Elis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agamemnon" title="Agamemnon">Agamemnon</a> (Ἀγαμέμνων), a king of Mycenae and commander of the Greek armies during the Trojan War</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agasthenes" title="Agasthenes">Agasthenes</a>, a king of Elis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Agenor_and_Phoenix" class="mw-redirect" title="Agenor and Phoenix">Agenor</a> (Αγήνωρ), a king of <a href="/wiki/Phoenicia" title="Phoenicia">Phoenicia</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alcinous" title="Alcinous">Alcinous</a> (Αλκίνους or Ἀλκίνοος), a king of <a href="/wiki/Phaeacia" class="mw-redirect" title="Phaeacia">Phaeacia</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alcmaeon_(mythology)" title="Alcmaeon (mythology)">Alcmaeon</a>, a king of Argos and one of the <a href="/wiki/Epigoni" title="Epigoni">Epigoni</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aleus" title="Aleus">Aleus</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Tegea" title="Tegea">Tegea</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphiaraus" title="Amphiaraus">Amphiaraus</a> (Ἀμφιάραος), a seer and king of Argos who participated in the Calydonian Boar hunt and the war of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_against_Thebes" title="Seven against Thebes">Seven against Thebes</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphictyon" title="Amphictyon">Amphictyon</a> (Ἀμφικτύων), a king of Athens</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amphion_and_Zethus" title="Amphion and Zethus">Amphion and Zethus</a>, twin sons of Zeus and kings of Thebes, who constructed the city's walls</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amycus" class="mw-redirect" title="Amycus">Amycus</a>, son of Poseidon and king of the <a href="/wiki/Bebryces" title="Bebryces">Bebryces</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anaxagoras_(mythology)" title="Anaxagoras (mythology)">Anaxagoras</a> (Ἀναξαγόρας), a king of Argos</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Anchises" title="Anchises">Anchises</a> (Αγχίσης), a king of <a href="/wiki/Dardanus_(city)" title="Dardanus (city)">Dardania</a> and father of Aeneas</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Arcesius" title="Arcesius">Arcesius</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Ithaca" title="Ithaca">Ithaca</a> and father of Laertes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Argeus_(king_of_Argos)" class="mw-redirect" title="Argeus (king of Argos)">Argeus</a>, a king of Argos</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Argus_(king_of_Argos)" title="Argus (king of Argos)">Argus</a>, a son of Zeus and king of Argos after Phoroneus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Assaracus" title="Assaracus">Assaracus</a>, a king of Dardania</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asterion" class="mw-redirect" title="Asterion">Asterion</a>, a king of <a href="/wiki/Crete" title="Crete">Crete</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Athamas" title="Athamas">Athamas</a> (Ἀθάμας), a king of <a href="/wiki/Orchomenus_(Boeotia)" title="Orchomenus (Boeotia)">Orchomenus</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Atreus" title="Atreus">Atreus</a> (Ἀτρεύς), a king of Mycenae and father of Agamemnon and Menelaus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Augeas" title="Augeas">Augeas</a> (Αυγείας), a king of Elis</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Autesion" title="Autesion">Autesion</a>, a king of Thebes</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bias_(mythology)" title="Bias (mythology)">Bias</a>, a king of Argos</li>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Amazons">Amazons</span></h3>
<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg/220px-Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg/330px-Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg/440px-Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2700" data-file-height="2160" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Bell-krater_Akhilleus_Penthesileia_MAN.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Achilles and Penthesileia (<a href="/wiki/Lucanian_vase_painting" title="Lucanian vase painting">Lucanian red-figure</a> <a href="/wiki/Krater" title="Krater">bell-krater</a>, late 5th century BC)</div></div></div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Aegea" title="Aegea">Aegea</a>, a queen of the Amazons</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Aella_(Amazon)" title="Aella (Amazon)">Aella</a> (Ἄελλα), an Amazon who was killed by Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Alcibie" title="Alcibie">Alcibie</a> (Ἀλκιβίη), an Amazonian warrior, killed by Diomedes at Troy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antandre" title="Antandre">Antandre</a> (Ἀντάνδρη), an Amazonian warrior, killed by Achilles at Troy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Antiope_(Amazon)" title="Antiope (Amazon)">Antiope</a> (Ἀντιόπη), a daughter of Ares and sister of Hippolyta</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Areto" title="Areto">Areto</a> (Ἀρετώ), an Amazon</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Asteria_(mythology)#Amazon" title="Asteria (mythology)">Asteria</a> (Ἀστερία), an Amazon who was killed by Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bremusa" title="Bremusa">Bremusa</a> (Βρέμουσα), an Amazonian warrior, killed by Idomeneus at Troy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Celaeno" title="Celaeno">Celaeno</a> (Κελαινώ), an Amazonian warrior, killed by Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Eurypyle_(Amazon)" title="Eurypyle (Amazon)">Eurypyle</a> (Εὐρυπύλη), an Amazon leader who invaded Ninus and Babylonia</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hippolyta" title="Hippolyta">Hippolyta</a> (Ἱππολύτη), a queen of Amazons and daughter of Ares</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hippothoe" title="Hippothoe">Hippothoe</a> (Ἱπποθόη), an Amazonian warrior, killed by Achilles at Troy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Iphito" title="Iphito">Iphito</a> (Ἰφιτώ), an Amazon who served under Hippolyta</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Lampedo" title="Lampedo">Lampedo</a> (Λαμπεδώ), an Amazon queen who ruled with her sister Marpesia</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Marpesia" title="Marpesia">Marpesia</a> (Μαρπεσία), an Amazon queen who ruled with her sister Lampedo</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Melanippe" title="Melanippe">Melanippe</a> (Μελανίππη), a daughter of Ares and sister of Hippolyta and Antiope</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Molpadia" title="Molpadia">Molpadia</a> (Μολπαδία), an Amazon who killed Antiope</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Myrina_(mythology)" title="Myrina (mythology)">Myrina</a> (Μύρινα), a queen of the Amazons</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orithyia_(Amazon)" title="Orithyia (Amazon)">Orithyia</a> (Ὠρείθυια), an Amazon queen</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Otrera" title="Otrera">Otrera</a> (Ὀτρήρα), an Amazon queen, consort of Ares and mother of Hippolyta</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pantariste" title="Pantariste">Pantariste</a> (Πανταρίστη), an Amazon who fought with Hippolyta against Heracles</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Penthesilea" title="Penthesilea">Penthesilea</a> (Πενθεσίλεια), an Amazon queen who fought in the Trojan War on the side of Troy</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thalestris" title="Thalestris">Thalestris</a> (Θάληστρις), a queen of the Amazons</li></ul>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Inmates_of_Tartarus">Inmates of Tartarus</span></h3>
<ul><li>The <a href="/wiki/Daughters_of_Danaus" class="mw-redirect" title="Daughters of Danaus">Danaides</a>, forty-nine daughters of Danaus who murdered their husbands and were condemned to an eternity of carrying water in leaky jugs</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ixion" title="Ixion">Ixion</a>, a king of the <a href="/wiki/Lapiths" title="Lapiths">Lapiths</a> who attempted to rape Hera and was bound to a flaming wheel in Tartarus</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sisyphus" title="Sisyphus">Sisyphus</a>, a king of Thessaly who attempted to cheat death and was sentenced to an eternity of rolling a boulder up a hill, only to watch it roll back down</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tantalus" title="Tantalus">Tantalus</a>, a king of Anatolia who butchered his son Pelops and served him as a meal to the gods; he was punished with the torment of starvation, food and drink eternally dangling just out of reach</li></ul>

<dl><dd>See <a href="/wiki/List_of_minor_Greek_mythological_figures" title="List of minor Greek mythological figures">List of minor Greek mythological figures</a></dd></dl>
